Try to assign the value for nummer variable after the print statement inside the loop. 
like this: 

        int nummer;
        do {
           System.out.print(&quot;Geef een getal: &quot;);
           nummer = invoer.nextInt();
        }while (nummer == STOP_TEKEN);

Learn carefully!!! For your case, two scenarios can occur. 

First, if your input is anything other than `0`, the `System.out.print()` will run only once. Because, as it is `do-while`, the statements inside `do` will run once and afterwards condition will not match as the number is not equal to `0`, and the loop will break.

Secondly, if your input is `0`, it will lead to **infinite loop** as the condition inside while always satisfies.

**Solution:**

You need to decrease the value of `nummer` in each iteration. Also, change your condition to `!=` in stead of `==`. Try like this:

```
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Scanner invoer = new Scanner(System.in);

    final int STOP_TEKEN = 0;

    int nummer = invoer.nextInt();

    do {
        System.out.print(&quot;Geef een getal: &quot;);
        nummer--;
    }
    while (nummer != STOP_TEKEN);
}
```

